04801nam a2200661Ia 9780824853402DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20152015hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248534027 a10.1515/97808248534022doi  a(DE-B1597)484580  a(OCoLC)1013962526  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aLA2383.J32bF87 2015 7aBIO0260002bisacsh04a370.92aB2231 aFuruki, Yoshiko, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe White Plum :bA Biography of Ume Tsuda, Pioneer of Women's Higher Education in Japan /cYoshiko Furuki. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (196 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Seedling -- t2. A Sapling On Foreign Soil -- t3. A Transplanted Tree -- t4. A Different Species -- t5. Among Cherry Trees -- t6. Still Growing -- t7. Ground to Share -- t8. The Plum Orchard -- t9. "Storm Last Night" -- tEpilogue: All Those Blossoms A Letter To Miss Tsuda -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the age of six, Ume Tsuda (1864-1929), the daughter of a progressive samurai, was sent on a mission by the Japanese government with four other girls to the United States. Their noble task was to first educate themselves in modern ways and Western learning, and then return to bring that gift to their sisters in Japan. Ume was cared for in the United States by Charles and Adeline Lanman, and she grew up in Washington, D.C., studying at private schools and becoming a Christian.At seventeen she finally returned to her country of birth, determined to carry out her mission. Back in Japan she found a new government quite unprepared to make use of her skills, but even more troubling was her startling self-discovery: unable to speak, read or write her native language fluently, she was faced with a homeland in which she was a foreigner, customs she did not understand, and a family she did not know and with whom she could not fully communicate. With the brave resilience of her namesake, the white plum that blooms in the last harsh days of winter, Ume was undaunted. Thriving on challenge, she devoted the rest of her life to seeking a way to achieve the goal of making modern higher education available to Japanese women for the first time. After several attempts, and two periods of advanced study abroad at Bryn Mawr College and Oxford, she eventually founded her own English School for Women. Later named Tsuda College, it has remained one of the bastions of women's higher education in Japan to this day. In her later years, Tsuda was not only an honored and influential educator in her own land and a founder of the Japanese YWCA but a cultural ambassador who met and exchanged correspondence with leading figures of her day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aWomen educatorszJapanvBiography. 0aWomenxEducation (Higher)zJapanxHistory. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311056413608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311075236640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082485340240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824853402423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824853402/original  a978-3-11-056413-6  UHP eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-075236-6  University of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015b2014  